consent:
Research study: Understanding Gaming Experiences



Research team: This study is run by researchers at Queen Mary University of London, University of York, Australian Catholic University, and Imperial College London: 

- Nick Ballou (n.b.ballou@qmul.ac.uk)

- Dr Alena Denisova (alena.denisova@york.ac.uk)

- Prof Richard Ryan (Richard.Ryan@acu.edu.au)

- Prof Sebastian Deterding (s.deterding@imperial.ac.uk)

 

Queen Mary Ethics of Research Committee Reference: QMERC20.565.DSEECS22.117

___________________________________________________________



Thank you for considering taking part in this study. Please take a moment to read the following. The participant compensation in this study accounts for the time required to review this information, so no need to rush.

 

Participation in this study is entirely optional. If you choose not to take part, simply close this page and there will be with no disadvantages and you will hear no more about it.

 

Study aim: We want to develop a new questionnaire for measuring positive and negative video gaming experiences.

 

Who can participate: To participate, you need to be:

- an active video game player (≥ 1 hour of gaming during an average week)  

- 18+ years old

- proficient in English

 

What to expect: You will be asked to recall a recent gaming experience, and then will rate a series of 76 statements on a scale from "strongly disagree" to "strongly agree" with reference to that experience. 

 

Because we are trialing many potential statements, some of them may be repetitive. We ask that if you choose to participate, you give your full attention to each of them.

 

In total, the study will take approximately 10 minutes.

 

Risks: Participating in this study is not expected to have any disadvantages, risks, or discomfort.

 

Confidentiality: We do not collect any personally identifying data. 

 

How we will use your data: Your data will be used in research publications and/or conference presentations. Your data, which is non-identifying, will be stored indefinitely on the Open Science Framework, so that the data underlying the conclusions of any published work will remain available for inspection.

 

Legal basis: We will process your personal data for research purposes under Article 6 (1) (e) of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR): Processing is necessary for the performance of a task carried out in the public interest.

 

Your rights to your data: Under the GDPR, you have a general right of access to your data, a right to rectification, erasure, restriction, objection or portability. You also have a right to withdrawal.

 

Withdrawal: You are free to withdraw within 1 month of data collection without any penalty or consequences. To do so, simply email the researcher with your Prolific ID. Your data will then be removed from the study. After 1 month, data will be publicly shared and withdrawal will no longer be possible. 

 

Contact information: If you would like additional information about the study, or wish to remove your data after the study has ended, please contact the lead researcher Nick Ballou (n.b.ballou@qmul.ac.uk). If this is unsuccessful or not appropriate, please contact the Queen Mary Ethics of Research Committee: research-ethics@qmul.ac.uk.

recall-pos-text: I felt that excitement with a xbox, when I bought it. I was playing Destiny for the first time in a console, it was a lot of mixed feelings because I'm used to a mouse and a keyboard. But that moment I decided to learn how to play with a controller. It was hard, but I learned it in the hard way.
It was fifa 23, i was playing division rivals which is sort of competetive mode, i felt kinda relaxed and honestly this game was pretty enjoyable, even tho it's known for its annoying side.

I recently played Counter Strike Global Offensive. In the game, you shoot at the opposing team. Emotions that accompany are joy, but also anger, excitement and sadness. Depending on the outcome of the game.
Game Days Gone. It is about a zombie apocalypse and you play with a character moves along the map riding a bike, killing zombies and bad people.
The last thing I played was Starcraft 2, I was playing co-op missions with another player to level up my account. I felt confident because I know the missions well and the characters I use.

The last time I played a video game for at least 20 minuts (it was way more than that, to be honest), was today, 31th of january 2023. The name of the game is World of Warcraft and I did all sorts of things. I completed dungeons with more real life players, I gathered herbs and ores so that I could sell them in the auction house for in game currency called Gold. I felt great and rewarded since the current itineration of the game is really fun (the expansion - WoW Dragonflight).
i played two games of league of legends this afternoon ,at first i was a bit annoyed because we lost and our team was flaming eachother then i clamed myself a bit because we won the second game

I  played euro truck simulator 2,and I  took a delivery for  2500km with my own truck, I managed to drive 2400km without crashing  and then I started relaxing. Just after that I crashed and my truck got 80% damage. That was reallyy sad because I didn't get paid

My most recent experience was playing Elite Dangerous in VR on PC, with a flight stick and throttle. It is a space trader/combat/exploration game. During my two-hour session I completed missions with the goal being to acquire credits for a better ship. 
I really like the game because of how completely you get absorbed into it, and the immersion afforded by VR. It really allows you to fulfill your "spaceship captain/explorer" fantasies.

The most recent game i played was FIFA 23 and since i didnt have much time, i only played 30/40 minutes, which equals to 4/5 games of rivals. The gameplay was awful, couldn't concentrate so i think i lost 3 and won 2. I felt kinda angry after a while and soon turned off.
I played 'Dead by Deadlight', it's an asymmetrical PvP game, where there is a killer and survivors. I mostly play the killer role, and it can get quite stressful and at the same time exciting.

League of Legends
i lost, of course.
how i feel?
terrible, frustrated, i always got a player who is garbabge

The games was Sunset Override.
Its a game about an apocalypse where everyone turns a mutant because of a energy drink and you as the main character must survive and find a exit of the apocalypse.
The game relies on movement a lot.
You are able to grind, bounce and parkour in almost every surface.
The games is very funny and mocks itself, the video game characters know they are stuck in a video game and joke about that.
The game is very happy, sunny and gives sense of freedom, do whatever you want how you want.
I feel nice when Im playing the game.
Escape From Tarkov, Tactical shooter, main purpouse is PVP, looting and survival. It's pretty stresfull but rewarding

Payday2, the game is based on making heists, not just normal bank heist, but museums, docks, trains, etc etc. I feel different, since is based on something that 99% of the people never will do it in real life, so give u the opportunity to enjoy something that outerwise u would never experiece
The game was Minecraft, I played with my friend. We built some new buildings together and chatted. It was relaxing after a long and stressful day.

Today I played FIFA 23. I was very interested playing it, since I didn't play any FIFA game since FIFA 20, so I decided to login to EA and use the 10 hours trial. It was a bit nostalgic and I kinda got hooked up to it right away.
I played Monster Hunter World, in which I hunted several endgame monsters, it is a really challenging experience, but very fulfilling once you succeed

It was Baldur's Gate 3 Early Access. I was playing as a lone-wolf adventurer and I felt totally entertained with in-game dialogs, graphics and encounters. It was like a good fantasy adventure book or TV series but interactive.

i played a game called hearthstone  a couple of hours ago for like a hour and half, i was ranking up in hearthstone ranked with a new deck i created, it was challanging but fun its a game where one mistake can cost you the game.
It was Call of Duty Modern Warfare 2. The game was fun, fast paced, dynamic. I felt amused for a while then, kind of bored.
League of Legends. I played with some friends one the rotating game modes. It was pretty fun.

The last game I played for more than 20 minutes was gta v roleplay. I was kidnapped and held hostage in a major bank robbery. Which was frustrating because it wasn't what I wanted however I found it funny because the muggers made jokes and it's all just a game

Grand tourismo

Car game where you participate in races to earn money or to upgrade your car collection. I felt very happy playing the game.
It as Valorant, i felt nervous to win a round. We were missing one person bc of afk, but still menaged to win. We were shooting, planting spike and dying.
I played torchlight 2, it was very enjoyable and peaceful to play because I didn't do anything demanding except fishing for items in the game
I played World of Warcraft. I did some group content with my friends. The game isn't as fun as it used to be but it's still decent and i get to chat with my friends while playing.
i was playing lol. i was trying to learn how to play with new champions. I felt excited and full of energy.

League of Legends. I had not played for some time so it felt good to play again. 
I played some casual games in the free time that I had.
The last game I played was League of Legends. I was having fun despite losing. We had good teamwork and there was no toxic player on our team.

I played Resident Evil: Village recently. It's a very nice game with great graphics. I loved the game ambient, very creepy, it has some scares. The gameplay was nice, first person shooter unlike the first games from this series.

It was a league of legends game, an aram, i got thresh and we dominated early game but the enemy team had better scaling champions so mid game they started catching up and late game they completely annhilated us. It was a bit sad losing but it was real fun

I played rocksmith , i was trying to learn a new song, i really enjoy playing this game because its with a real guitar and i feel like i am really playing my favorite songs, i feel like a rockstar everytime i play this game.
I was playing Sonic Frontiers. I spent my time running around map, finding treasures and completing puzzles. I had much fun and i felt relaxed.
It was a League of Legends match, I felt good because I played nice and we won the game and I feel like I contributed a lot to help my teammates during the match.
I played Dead Cells, it really made me feel fast and coordinated (since killing is so fast in it).
I was playing "Hades". I had fun, moved the main plot a bit forward, i did a few sidequests. At the end I was a bit frustrated because i wasn't able to pass a boss yet. Overall it was fun
It was Elden Ring and I was farming a good sword for 40 minutes by killing skeletons. I was feeling a little bored but also excited once it finally dropped.
The last game I played was Call of Duty: MWII, where I played an online session. In-game I feel somewhat tense as it's a very fast-paced game but it helps me to unwind at the end of the day.
Rocket League. I failed a lot of goals. It feels exciting but frustrating at the same time

I played League with some friends. It wasn't really pleasant. It feels like games are becoming faster and adapting to the younger generation, who is focused on too many micro mechanics. It's getting harder for me, and making me and others slowly lose interest in games.

The last game I played was "Ace Attorney" on the Nintendo Switch. It's a game about being a lawyer and trying to prove that your clients are innocent on trial, while presenting evidence and contradictions in witnesses' testimonies. I got really immersed in the lawyer role, getting that "aha!" feeling every time I proved something right. I also felt very clever when solving the case. I get very connected to my clients and I go above and beyond to prove their innocence, even though they are fictional. Until now, I had lost in a single trial and that raised the stakes for me.
Turn based strategy game, i intended to play for just an hour but i kinda lost the sense of the clock
The last game I played for more than 20 minutes was league of legends, it was a ranked game that I ended up winning and so I felt good.

In the last gaming session I played Assassin's Creed Syndicate. I impersonated both Jacob and Evie for two different approaches to the game: the former focused on action, the latter on stealth. I enjoyed playing a few side quests, although the game is poorly optimised so it created some frustration due to framerate drops (I'm someone who cares a lot about graphics)

I played apex legends with a friend, we lost a couple of matches , i felt good at first because we didnt play apex for quite some time, but when we started losing we just gave up and went to play another game

The last time I played a video game was League of Legends a few days ago, I remember that I felt pretty good for having the time to play a few games, my team was pretty good, I was a bit rusty but I played the best I could, at least In the end we won several games that day.
I played Assassins creed black flag. I completed the game and felt really sucked into the story, the world and the gameplay. I couldnt stop when I started playing.

The last video game I played was "Cuphead". Since I had to defeat several bosses it was very I kept dying over and over again, so I felt really frustrated, but that didn't stop me from trying again until I was fed up.
I played a simulation game helping to save a world from overtaken by evil ppl. I felt amazing because i was helping the ppl in the game
It was Valorant, I felt good because I was playing with my friends

I played League of Legends 10 minutes ago. It was fun but stressful. We almost lost but were able to climb back and win with lots of team effort. I felt stressed, relieved and completely emerged in the game. After it finished, I struggled to go back to my house/university duties, but I managed to snap out of it and log off.

The game I was playing was Harvestella. It is a Final Fantasy like videogame with features of farming simulation games such as Story of Seasons and Stardew Valley, or even Rune Factory, so basically you go completing quests for npcs, growing your crops, tending to your animals, etc. I really enjoy this kind of simulation games since I was a child, and having a so I felt quite excited.
I recently played GTA V, but on a Roleplay server. I've only been playing something like that lately and I get a lot of enjoyment out of it, it's a fun way to kill boredom.
It was yesterday. I played League of Legends. I had wins and loses and I enjoyed it despite of the loses because I play this game for fun.

Genshin impact, a gacha open world game with beautiful graphics and music, super immesive and fun to play. In this game you collect different characters through a gacha system and use their abilities to kill monsters, complete story quests or even just explore. 
I find this game super relaxing, fun and I play it everyday.

The last game I played was Elden Ring 2 days ago,I was trying to beat a major boss that I was stuck for hours.I was really enjoying the game but at the same time I was nervous cause I really wanted to kill it and it was hard!

League of Legends: Teamfight Tactics
I could not find the characters I was rolling for and that made me lose the game. I felt tilted since I lost 3 games in a row.
Lately I got back to playing Borderlands 2. I felt very nostalgic since its an older piece. Had the same fun as years before

I was playing the rogue-lite card game Slay the Spire. I tried to beat the most difficult level of the game with the character called The Watcher. I have attempted it many times, and because it is very difficult, I was not able to achieve victory this time either. I was very relaxed. The most recent game that I've played is CS:GO. In fact, you could say I'm a veteran player, as I've played that game for over 3000 hours (according to my Steam profile). So me and my teammates played a competitive match on a map called "Anubis" (kind of a new map), and we managed to win 16-13 (that match took around 40 minutes). The best thing about competitive games is the "flow" state that they allow you to enter. That is something I usually experience a few times per match. Especially in emotionally charged situations. That "flow" makes me somehow connected to the game on a psychic level. My field of view shrinks a bit, which lets me focus on the game more, my reaction time gets way faster, and I completely cut off all the stimuli outside of the game. You should read about that, it's sort of a common thing for pro players, and that might be helpful for your study.

I play video games very regularly, in long sessions. The last time I played a computer game for at least 20 minutes was yesterday. My friends and I played GTA Online. We come back to this game from time to time to spend time together. The game is not about some predetermined activities, and above all about spending time together, where the game is simply the background.
This time we restocked parcel warehouses to later sell them as a group. I felt great during these activities, but it was mainly because of this opportunity to interact with friends. The gameplay itself would seem boring to most.
There are many such games in which I immerse myself and feel full immersion, such as Red Dead Redemption, in which I spent hundreds of hours and completed this game many times.
I also like games that are seemingly boring to most people, such as ETS. When I'm driving in ETS, I like to listen to the radio and watch the scenery. It is also a time when I can talk to someone, e.g. on discord, or watch a video on YouTube or Netflix.
Anyway, games are all about having fun. The point is that every game user should be able to use them in any way that makes them happy, as long as it does not interfere with the fun of other people.
